[0.018, "o", "\u001b[H\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mGhost activity is benign-looking shell churn. Evidence: recently_exited is mostly short-lived\u001b[m                                 \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mgit/starship/zsh/hyprctl/cliphist/systemd-userwork with tiny lifespans and no standout outbound pattern.\u001b[0m                      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mIf you want, next I can drill into 1) the Antigravity/Electron tree, 2) the live godshell processes, or 3) shell history for\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204muser raul before you send snapshot two.\u001b[0m                                                                                       \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou❯ \u001b[0mwhat new processes spawned on this new snapshot?                                                                         \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0m◈ summary\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153m11 groups · 49 processes · 38 exited · \u001b[1;38;2;255;136;102mtop: /usr/lib/antigravit… 33.5%\u001b[0m\u001b[0m                                         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell❯ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mNo new active processes spawned between the two snapshots. Evidence: every active PID in the 13:17:47 snapshot was\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204malready present in the 13:17:11 snapshot.\u001b[0m                                                                                     \u001b[K\r\n\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mNew activity exists only in recently exited processes. Evidence: new exited PIDs added in the second snapshot are hyprctl\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m260915, 260917, 260912, 260914, 260909, 260911, 260896, 260898; all are very short-lived 4–9 ms processes with 50 opens and\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1 connection each.\u001b[0m                                                                                                            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou❯ \u001b[0mare you sure?                                                                                                            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell❯ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mYes, based on the snapshot data I have.\u001b[0m                                                                             \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mEvidence: I compared the active PID sets from both summary outputs. The second snapshot’s active PIDs are the same as the\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mfirst:\u001b[0m                                                                                                                        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1. Electron/Antigravity tree: 4015, 4061, 4109, 4129, 4130, 4188, 4354, 4402, 4884, 9500, 250889, 250891, 250968\u001b[0m              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m2. systemd user tree: 2123, 2159, 2264, 2304, 2310, 2373, 2432, 13671\u001b[0m                                                         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m3. Hyprland tree: 2192, 258219, 258228, 258230, 259229, 259240, 259242\u001b[0m                                                        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m4. Chrome tree: 2649, 2700, 239519, 239544, 253307, 256839, 256873\u001b[0m                                                        